segments.text: Mrs. Grace Jackson, Bryan, Texas, 83 years old, interviewed Monday, 24th of March, 1975, by Adela Lopez and Jim Crisp.
Excuse me, Mrs. Jackson, could you tell us just a little bit about where you're from or a little bit about yourself or what brought you here in the first place?
How far back?
Where I'm from?
Directly?
Yes, ma'am.
To here?
Oh, we came here from Rush, Texas.
That's where the insane asylum is.
I'm glad to get out.
Pardon?
Where is Rust?
Rust?
It's in East Texas.
East Texas?
Close to Kilgore and Henderson, around that territory.
Is that where y'all's family was from before?
No, no, no.
You see, my husband was a Methodist minister, and that's why I asked you how far back I must go, because we were gypsies.
We went wherever the bishop sent us.
We just gypsied from the coast all over the world, you know, to different places.
That was where we came from here.
Where was your...
Family from?
Okay, from Arkansas.
Arkansas.
Lead Hill, Arkansas, that's right.
And then we spent most of our lives at the Fed of Arkansas, where the Razorbacks are, that whipped us in the basketball, and we didn't like it.
Joe, what caused Joe?
To come here just because a bishop sent you here?
Yes.
They changed at that time.
It was a rule in our church that we move every four years.
So when our four years was up at Russ, they sent us here.
They appointed us here.
We had no idea where we would go until we went to conference.
And when they sent us, they told us that it was a boys' school and they were sending us here primarily to work with the boys.
And you'll be surprised to know there's only 900 here then.
And I thought, oh my soul, 900 boys, what'll I do with them?
And they were all khaki-clad then, you know.
And it was, well, it was just military.
But I decided the only thing I could do would be to just make a Christian home for them.
And most of them called me mom.
And they felt just as free to come to my kitchen and go to my refrigerator as they did in their own homes.
Are you referring to the boys out of A&M?
Referring to the boys of A&M.
And what a change there's been since then.
And there was just 900 boys?
Just 900 boys.
But I thought I never saw as many boys in all my life.
And for things that, you know, people weren't as fluent then as they are now.
Very few of them had cars.
So we had open house for them on Wednesday night.
They were out.
They could stay out later.
See...
At that time, they just did everything between military pistols.
But they could stay out later on Wednesday nights and on Sunday nights.
So those were the nights that I had them in my home.
And we just played all kinds of games and did things like that.
And I will say this.
I never had one to cross my threshold that wasn't a perfect gentleman.
And that's saying a lot.
In four years' time,
They never used a cuss word.
They were never.
And another thing that we were so proud of at that time, oh, a big class distinction.
You know, freshman, senior, what have you.
But when they came to our house, everybody was on a level.
We had no seniors.
We had no freshmen.
We were just all one.
We enjoyed our work with them so much.
And we had them, I remember one night down there, I forget how many countries there was representing.
Oh, just Afghanistan, and Pakistan, and India, and Japan, and China.
They were just from all over the world.
These two plaques here, and that one over there is from Japan.
These are from China.
And those people are great on giving gifts.
And they all went home for Christmas and these boys were so far away they couldn't get there and back if they had the money to go.
It cost something to go that far.
So we bought the biggest turkey we could find and had 12 of them down home.
That's just about all I could accommodate them on for dinner.
And you know, I got gifts for the rest of the time we was here.
Every Christmas they'd send me, they'd still send me gifts.
And these are some of them.
This was a beautiful dress.
You know, they were all married.
They were married, their people married them.
They were like the ten, who did they call them?
You know what I'm trying to say?
They had matchmakers, you know, over there at 12 and 10.
So this was the dress that one of their wives selected.
It fit her.
He said I was about the size of his wife.
And we used it for all the dances.
And the girls would borrow it and have the pictures made.
They were just running it.
So I had it cut up, the skirt.
I still have the blouse, perfectly beautiful.
What was it like when you first got here?
Oh!
It looked like a desert.
A desert?
Well, yes.
We came from East Texas, from these trees everywhere and houses.
You know, it was a...
It was just a place where everybody lived.
And we got out here.
There wasn't anything here but the college and that old main building.
And the post office was clear across the railroad track over there, way across the railroad track, and a place just about as big as this living room.
My husband got that changed.
And there was no houses on this side of the campus at all, the north gate.
There's one or two buildings at the north gate.
We liked A&M so much that Mr. Jackson bought a tract of land from the north gate down to the Brine, down to the city of Brine.
He bought nine acres right in there.
And you know, before we could build a house on it, we had to put on our own lives, water, and gas.
We had to put all that in ourselves to get it to our own home.
And of course, everybody that
hooked on then as the town grew.
Everybody hooked on, tied on to ours.
We eventually got our money back and made a little bit, but that's how barren everything.
My house was the only one on that side of the house, and you want to know how come you didn't get that house?
They had a load of three-room parsons in the bath that the former pastor had used, and they wanted to sell it and build the pastor a decent home.
So they had Dodgers struck.
Those little old Leafers just give out, you know, having an auction.
And there's been an auction that three-room house off.
It was a real cold day, and you know, people aren't very responsive when it's cold.
So my husband thought, well, he'd just make a bid on it just to get it started.
And you know what happened?
He bid $100, and one of our members was there, and he just wriggled around through that audience like a snake.
He said, don't outbid that preacher.
It's not worth any more than that.
He said, let him have it.
I don't know what he wants with it.
But he said, let him have it if he wants.
And wouldn't anybody outbid us?
And there he was with that thing on his hand.
We didn't have an inch of ground in the world to set it on.
And it had to be off by a certain time.
You see, that was the main idea was to get rid of the thing, get it off the lot there so they could build the other one.
So we had time to find anybody to sell us any land.
Boyd owned most of it on that side of town.
And he was only allowed to sell.
enough to pay the taxes.
See, it was all tied up in the state.
So he was allowed to sell enough to pay his taxes.
And that's how we got four or five little lots over there to set that house on.
Well, then you live pretty close to the campus because Boyett Street is just on this side of University Drive.
Pardon?
You live right on the other side.
Oh, yes.
See, I just live two blocks from the post office.
My apartment's, I have 13 apartments over there now.
And before we got that little old three-room house moved down there, everybody in town tried to rent.
You know, there wasn't any apartments around here.
No, no, nothing.
And everybody was trying to find a place to live.
And so Mr. Jackson conceived the idea that if they were that much in demand, he'd just get it down there and make it a two-story house.
And he did, and it's been around ever since.
And then we built our own home on the big corner lot.
Eight bedrooms and five baths.
And I kept those girls.
They didn't have any motels or hotels.

or anything and so when the boys had their dates they had to stay in private homes and I could keep 16 you see easy and the night you know they built that slab over there you know where I'm talking about the slab where they had the outdoor dance I don't know how you do or not it's over there in that old shell looking building close to the
Well, okay, the night that opened up, I had eight cots.
My living room was bigger than this over there.
And I had eight cots just right along there.
And I slept in the kitchen on the cot.
Everybody wanted to come, and there was nowhere to put them.
And mothers would call me from Galveston or San Antonio or anywhere, and they said, well, they all knew I was a minister's wife, and they knew I run a decent place.
And they'd say, I don't care where you put her.
Just let her sleep anywhere, just so I know she's down there with you.
And that's what we had.
And so I didn't know that my son and Mr. Jackson were coming.
And lo and behold, about the time the girls were all dressing and so on, here came my husband.
He was pastor of a church in Houston.
And so...
When they came, there wasn't a place anywhere in the house they could go without seeing your old woman anywhere.
They had to drive clear back to Houston.
My own husband and my own son couldn't find a place to stay in college.
Dad said, if you ever do this again, you don't have to do that.
And I said, well, they just kept coming.
I didn't know what to do, and I didn't know you were coming.
And while I was here in Mr. Jackson and Houston, I must explain that.
See, that was right after I'd gotten out of the hospital.
And I couldn't do my, I couldn't play my role as a minister's wife.
I tried it.
I went down there with him after the appointment was made in Houston.
And, oh, every time I do anything, the church, they'd send me back to the hospital.
So the bishop, the man that was out right over us, he said, don't you have a relative?
Couldn't you send her anywhere?
I said, she just can't do this.
I said, it would kill her.
I took everything so seriously because I love my work and
We worked many times and never would do a bid.
So we conceived the idea of me coming up here and running that house instead of renting it out.
So that's why I was here and my husband was down there.
I want to make that clear.
But, oh, I had so many rich and rare and real experiences in that house, both with the boys and the girls.
It was just a...
I'd always wanted a girl, and I had the sweetest little red-headed boy you ever did see.
But then once I had all the girls and boys, too, I could manage.
Was there any big happenings here, like any of the floods or anything?
Or drafts that you remember that really affected your job?
No, we were here during the Depression, but that's like it is now.
The people on the campus don't know anything about it.
They don't depend on crops failures and so on.
They get their checks through the fiscal office just like they do now.
We were here.
No, we didn't have any drafts.
How was the depression, though?
I mean, the people on the campus?
Well, the people on campus didn't know this having one.
That's what I said.
They got their checks every month anyway.
And most of them lived on the campus in those faculty homes, you see.
Most of them lived on campus.
And so we didn't realize this having one.
We got our check every month.
They got theirs.
See, a lot of these people that have to depend on
their crops and their cattle and things like that.
They do feel it, but we didn't have any of those kind of people here.
We just had seven men on our fishing board at that time.
Now they have between 50 and 60, I think.
So you see, that's how things have been.
Well, how did it affect the other people?
I mean, besides, didn't it sort of slow down the work here?
It slowed down with the boys, I think.
They were pretty hard.
The boys were kids harder than we did, and that's when they, well, I don't know how to express it.
They had these what they called project houses, and they'd rent a great big house and put as many boys, and the college would rent the house, put a matron over it.
and put as many boys in there as they could possibly squeeze in, bunk beds and what have you.
And the only way they could go to school was to bring enough out of their deep freezers at home or enough eggs or butter or something to put in that kitchen.
Every boy brought his share, you see.
And then this lady that they had hired to run that thing

cook and serve now that it did affect the boys that way because a lot of the boys couldn't come to school for what they call those project houses but and yet the boys that lived like that crowded areas and they'd go home intermittently and bring them back enough and you know what they'd do they'd bring me back a roast too
I got fed like they did.
And they just, and yet they made the best grades of anybody.
They made the best grades of anybody.
They realized, you know, what they were here for.
Well, did it affect these businesses down in Bryan?
I notice there's a lot of old businesses there that look like that.
Well, they recently, it's just gradually deteriorated.
When we were here, brine was at its height because it wasn't anything out of college, you see.
There was no stores and things like that at college.
Oh, just something here and there and yonder and in the mountains, anything.
We all had to do all of our shopping at brine, even our, most of our groceries, we had to buy it down there.
No, college-fed brine.
You see, it always has.
It still does.
No, Brian has just gradually gone down because college has gone up.
Everything's come this way, you see.
No, I don't think Brian felt it like most towns do because they had college here to feed them.
See, most towns didn't have that.
And it did make a difference.
But any churches here...
Well, the Presbyterian Church and the Episcopal Church, I think they met in the YMCA.
And the Lutheran Church met in what was once Guyon Hall.
Of course, that's been torn down.
You may not be familiar with that.
But anyway, you see, it was a situation.
They didn't have any school, any grammar school.
I sent my son, Brian, to Allen Academy.
Oh, they had just a low-frame building where the kids on the campus went, but it wasn't adequate.
I wouldn't have sent mine there.
The professors did because...
Well, it moved them, too, to see.
They were in a tough spot there, but I was in a different spot.
So I sent mine, too.
No, just everything has changed so much.
But I'd rather you'd ask me the questions, because I don't know what you're going to do.
But did it really start growing, or...
Did the war really affect it after the Depression and then the war?
Yes.
When the war came, you've seen the plaque on the student center of how many boys.
In fact, A&M boys won the war.
And several of our boys that were the most faithful ones in the church gave their lives for your freedom and mine.
One day here, there was two or three boys.
We got messages of two or three the same day.
The whole campus was in tears.
Just the whole campus was in tears.
Yes, it began to grow after that.
The boys came home and business, you know, everywhere was just different.
And the situations in their hometowns were different.
You see, so it began to go right to that.
And I just can't believe they got 20,000 out there.
I just can't believe they got 20,000 boys out that college, and girls.
And when we were here, there was four or five girls on the campus.
Three of them were old maids, and the Aggies wouldn't look at them.
They were too old.
And the other three were high school girls, and they were too young.
So when we had parties for the boys,
And party was my middle name.
We've always worked with young people.
That's been my responsibility ever since we were married.
And I figured if I played with them all week, they'd come and pray with me on Sunday.
And they did.
The house was always full.
But when I'd have my parties, I'd have to go to Brian.
Well, I had two or three girls at Brian that I phoned.
And they filled their cars up full.
See, the boys weren't allowed to go with them.
Oh, there'd been such a change in that campus.
And when the party was over at 11, 30, or 12-something, they had to be back up to college.
And Dad and I would have to take those girls home, you know.
Me and I, I never did go to bed.
But I was having such a good time, and I was young and gay then.
I didn't mind it.
I didn't mind it.
But when did they...
They used to commute by this railroad.
Yes, now that was for my day.
That was for my day.
The railroad wasn't here.
The little trolley wasn't here.
The tracks had already been up and everything when we came.
See, those are in the code, too.
No, the boys didn't have, I'll tell you how they got to Brian.
We didn't have a picture show or anything out here, and they just hitchhiked.
You'd see 8 and 10 or 12 on the corner, and everybody would pick them up, just as many as they could hang on the car, including me.
And now they won't even stop for them.
They're afraid to.
Well, and then with 20,000, you're bound to get a few you don't want.
No, they just did their hitchhiking instead of using that trolley.
But I think one of the biggest changes that's been made, I don't know if you want this or not, is in that campus.
See, there wasn't any of those buildings there.
It was just all...
campus, except a few streets that had those professors' phones on it.
And the rest of it was just me.
I've sat here and watched it, but I don't believe it.
Watched it grow and still don't believe it.
But now there's every denomination in the world here at church on every corner.
But you said when y'all first came here, there were only two churches?
Our church and the Presbyterian didn't have a church.
They met in the Y.
And so did the Episcopalians.
And the Lutherans had rooms in the Guyon Hall.
But they had their morning services, and then they worshipped with us in the evening.
They worshipped with us in the evening.
We had pretty nice evening services.
Brother, I mean, Major Dunn was a drunk, wasn't he?
had charge of the band then.
And he would bring, oh, 18 or 20 of those band members at our church on Sunday night.
And Mrs. Norton, the coach's wife, was our pianist.
So we were very much involved with A&M.
And those two people would really draw a crowd.
And Coach Norton had a daughter that would draw a crowd anywhere.
She'd come with her mother.
Well, were the churches in Bryan pretty well established, and the students weren't going to there?
No, they wouldn't.
Well, they had no way of getting there.
You see, in the first place, they had no way of getting there.
And our church and the, oh yes, the Baptist church was here.
I didn't mention them.
They were here.
They had a little church here.
And Brother...
Brother Brown and Brother Anson and my husband were the three main pastors.
The other churches that I met, the Presbyterians and the Episcopalians, they really didn't have a pastor.
They just met and had Sunday school in those buildings up there.
You see, just to hold the group together.
But now, everybody, including the Jews, well, everybody, the Church of Christ, the Seventh-day Adventists, they all have churches now, as you know.
But ours and the Baptist's were the only two real permanent churches on the campus.
You mentioned one thing, how being here affected me and what it had done to me.
It did a lot.
It just did a lot for me, for those boys.
Well, they were the sweetest mean boys I ever saw.
They were just sweet, but they'd play every kind of joke on you, on Earth.
And yet they were just perfect gentlemen.
And you hear now of so much thievery going on and stealing and things like that.
You never heard of such a thing then.
In fact, one of the boys made his way through school by selling homemade candy.
I think his mother gave him a lift at that point.
And you know what he did?
He had a table in one of those halls up there and would put it out in a box and cover it with cellophane paper and everything where it was sanitary.
And with another box, two pieces for a nickel.
And he said he never lost a dime.
Nobody would take a piece of candy without dropping a nickel in that plate.
And now here they rest them every night for students.
See, it's a different...
And when you had boys like that, you know, they did something for you.
I just loved them for their, well, for their inward search and their outward reach and their upward look.
They were that type of boys.
We were sent here to help them, and they helped us because we wouldn't have betrayed their confidence for anything in the world.
And I had the pleasure of having so many of their mothers at home on Mother's Day.
You know, and things like that.
And when they come down, I keep their mothers, a lot of them, in the homes.
So it was a very happy relationship.
And that's why we decided right then we wanted to stay here the rest of our lives.
Because we thought every one of those 20,000 agas were going to be just like that 900.
And many of them are.
Many of them are.
You wouldn't expect to find a few in 20,000.
You know.
Della and I were talking on our way up.
I don't know, are you familiar with Mom's, this boarding house that used to be back on the other side?
No.
I was just wondering, I thought maybe you might know her.
Evidently she'd been here for, you know, since the war or something like that, selling meals, homemade meals.
It's on 25th Street.
That wasn't the Bell, Ms. Farmer, the Bell home, was it?
You know, I'm not familiar with that.
I'm just curious on that.
No, I wish I could give you some information on that.
It's an itty place where a lot of Aggies go out there, and the food is really expensive.
It used to be like, for a dollar a plate, all you would want.
A lot of Aggies went out there.
And we're just trying to figure out how long they've been there.
Because I didn't know.
I know I had been out there about three years ago, and he had been there.
Well, I'll tell you.
Since my son graduated from A&M, and my husband was no longer on the faculty, I've lost contact with a lot of these things that have been
in vogue, I'd say, since then, you see.
And I've never, I don't believe I've ever heard of Moms.
There used to be a Mrs. Bell here right across the street from the First Methodist Church that served homemade meals.
And boy, the boys sure flocked in there.
And she served one for a dollar meal.
And she just put it on a big, long table.
And boy, you just eat until you...
Sounds like moms.
It must be similar.
But I'm not familiar with that.
I'm sorry.
But since you lost contact with the college, you're working locally with a community now?
Yes, I'm still a member of the church.
My husband's pastor of the A&M Methodist Church.
And he also served as a Wesley Foundation director and taught religious education in the college.
He had a big Bible class in the college.
They don't have that anymore.
I don't know why that would discontinue.
But he had a big class, and he was so proud of them.
And they were excellent students.
And if they deserved an A, he gave it to them.
And they called him in one time.
It seemed to be a rule that you just give so many A's and flunk the rest of them to make them, you know how that goes.
Well, Mr. Jackson said, I just cannot do that.
He said, if they deserve an A, I've just got to give it to them.
And he said, I'll let you have their papers, anybody that's familiar with the Bible.
And if you can't give them, if you see where I've made a mistake, he said, I'll correct it.

You see, we had three, now over here at our church, now that he was pastor for four years, they have three ministers and a Wesley Foundation worker, and they have four or five secretaries, paid, all paid.
And when we were here, we had the whole thing by ourselves.
But we only had 900 boys, whereas they have 20.
I don't know.
I couldn't say it.
So there's a lot of difference.
What about the people who sort of settled into College Station and Bryan since you've been here?
Has the main reason been the school, or are they really just different people coming in for the job?
Well, I believe a lot of them.
I mean, I won't say a lot of them.
I'll crack myself there and say a part of them have come on account of the schools.
both A&M and Allen Academy.
But most of them, I believe, have come from a commercial standpoint because this is the fastest growing area, you know, anywhere.
And I think they've come here from a commercial standpoint more than they have the schools.
You hate to think that, you know, but I just will be honest with you.
I do believe that this is true because we have so many things
that don't even pertain to the college that they come in here and all these pizza huts and hamburgers and things like that of course they've come to mcdowell but now the the we didn't have a motel
